\begin_layout Standard
\align left

\series bold
Definition: Rigid Body 
\series default
- A theoretical abstraction of non-deformable physical objects.
 Tangible
\series bold
 
\series default
objects, in the scope of everyday life, are made up of countless tiny particles
 (atoms).
 Simulating objects in a correct manner by use of particle systems is infeasible
 for providing real-time physics simulation on modern computers.
 Abstracting the atomic particle structure into a single continuous, solid,
 non-deformable object is an effective means to approximate correct physical
 interaction between objects.
 One further postulation about rigid bodies is that they must encompass
 a non-zero volume.
 This restriction will become useful and apparent in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align left
For the scope of this paper, it is assumed that rigid bodies are not destroyable.
 In other words, they cannot be split up into multiple pieces (a subject
 which is outside the scope of this discussion).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computer games make frequent use of rigid body physics, and in their fictional
 world, for the sake of gameplay and speed, many things can be considered
 a rigid body.
 In this scope, almost any physical object is simulated via rigid bodies.
 Some examples are rocks, walls, cars, the ground as well as other immutable
 environmental elements, and Acme-brand anvils (but only Acme-brand).
 Some examples of 
\emph on
non
\emph default
-rigid bodies are liquids and gasses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From here on, 
\series bold
rigid bodies
\series default
 will be referred to simply as 
\series bold
bodies
\series default
.
\end_layout

