\backslash
subsection{First Moment Of Inertia}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: First Moment Of Inertia
\series default
 is the fancy name for the property of a body commonly known as 
\series bold
mass
\series default
 (and from here on, it will be referred to as such).
 It is a positive scalar value, commonly notated as 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, and represents an object's resistance to linear acceleration (the scalar
 value 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

) from a given force (the scalar value 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
a=\frac{F}{m}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, increasing the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 (making the body heavier) will provide greater resistance to the applied
 force, resulting in a decreasing value of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 (assuming an unchanging value of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

).
 The above equation is equivalent to Newton's second law of motion, 
\begin_inset Formula $F=ma$
\end_inset

, as well as the following, where the division by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 indicates validity only when 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
m=\frac{F}{a}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Calculating the mass of an object is fairly simple.
 A rigid body must have a density function 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\hat{x}\right):\mathbb{R}^{d}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined over the volume it encompasses.
 The mass of the body is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
m=\begin{array}{cc}
\\\int & D\left(\hat{x}\right)\mathbf{dV}\\
V\end{array}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Commonly, the density function will be simplified to be constant, as would
 be the case for solid, homogeneous objects such as bricks or metal objects.
\end_layout

