\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Angle
\series default
 - In order to completely specify the orientation of a body in 3 dimensions,
 3 scalar values must be used, each an angle describing the rotation which
 the body undergoes in each coordinate plane.
 This method of specifying rotations is called 
\series bold
Euler angles
\series default
.
 Normally Euler angles specify rotations around the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axes (in that order), but for purposes of this paper, it will be specified
 in the order 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 If you think of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
axis as being forward, the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axis as being left, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 axis as being up, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
roll
\series default
 angle around the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
pitch
\series default
 angle around the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axis, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
yaw
\series default
 angle around the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 axis.
 All angles specify counterclockwise rotation around their respective coordinate
 axes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to look at the way these angles work is from the perspective
 of the space being transformed.
 Euler angles are commonly used in 3D computer games to completely specify
 the orientation of an object in space.
 From a literal first person perspective, the 
\series bold
yaw
\series default
 angle (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

) changes when one turns their head left or right, or shakes their head
 'no'.
 The 
\series bold
pitch
\series default
 angle (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) changes when one looks up or down, or nods their head 'yes'.
 The 
\series bold
roll
\series default
 angle (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

) changes when one rotates their head while looking forward, e.g.
 to attempt to read a sign which is hanging upside-down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A complete Euler angle rotation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 consists of 3 separate rotation matrices which specify the rotation for
 each of the angles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{R}=\mathbf{R}_{\theta}\mathbf{R}_{\phi}\mathbf{R}_{\psi}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transformations are applied in this specifc order (keep in mind that
 the matrices are multiplied on the left of the vector) so that the axes
 of rotation remains consistent with the axes of the head (referring to
 the head-turning analogy above).
 If the matrices were applied in reverse order, the axis of rotation would
 be absolute, and would give unintuitive results in the head-turning scenario.
 For example, if the yaw angle was 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

 the head would turn 
\begin_inset Formula $90$
\end_inset

 degrees to the left; if then a pitch angle was applied, the head would
 not tilt back or forward as expected, but rather would tilt left and right
 as if a roll angle was being applied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each of the atomic rotation matrices are as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{R}_{\theta}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta & 0\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1\end{array}\right]\qquad\mathbf{R}_{\phi}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\phi & 0 & \sin\phi\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\sin\phi & 0 & \cos\phi\end{array}\right]\qquad\mathbf{R}_{\psi}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\psi & -\sin\psi\\
0 & \sin\psi & \cos\psi\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

, the composite rotation matrix, is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{R}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta & 0\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\phi & 0 & \sin\phi\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\sin\phi & 0 & \cos\phi\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\psi & -\sin\psi\\
0 & \sin\psi & \cos\psi\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{R}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta & 0\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\phi & \sin\psi\sin\phi & \cos\psi\sin\phi\\
0 & \cos\psi & -\sin\psi\\
-\sin\phi & \sin\psi\cos\phi & \cos\psi\cos\phi\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{R}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\phi\cos\theta & \sin\psi\sin\phi\cos\theta-\cos\psi\sin\theta & \cos\psi\sin\phi\cos\theta+\sin\psi\sin\theta\\
\cos\phi\sin\theta & \sin\psi\sin\phi\sin\theta+\cos\psi\cos\theta & \cos\psi\sin\phi\sin\theta-\sin\psi\cos\theta\\
-\sin\phi & \sin\psi\cos\phi & \cos\psi\cos\phi\end{array}\right]\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Angular Velocity
\series default
 is a vector value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 It describes the axis of rotation, and its magnitude is the scalar value
 of the body's angular speed.
 Rotating a body, whose orientation is specified by Euler angles, around
 an arbitrary axis requires a bit of conversion work to know what the changes
 in Euler angles actually are.
