\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Torque
\series default
 is the angular analog to force.
 It is also a vector value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tau}$
\end_inset

, and is the derivative of rotational angular momentum (which will be explained
 in the next section) with respect to time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\tau}=\frac{\mathbf{d}}{\mathbf{dt}}\hat{L}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align left
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
subsection{Second Moment Of Inertia And Angular Momentum}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align left

\series bold
Definition: Second Moment Of Inertia
\series default
 is the fancy wording for the rotational equivalent of a body's mass.
 It is a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

, which satisfies the equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{\tau}=\frac{\mathbf{d}}{\mathbf{dt}}\mathbf{M}\hat{\omega}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, torque is equal to the product of the second moment of inertia
 and the angular acceleration vector, or the derivative of 
\series bold
angular momentum
\series default
 with respect to time.
 It is commonly referred to by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}$
\end_inset

, however this standard will be avoided in this paper to avoid confusing
 it with the symbol for the identity matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Angular Momentum
\series default
 is a vector value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

, which is the product of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

second moment of inertia tensor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (which will be discussed in the next section) and the angular velocity,
 plus an additional term which will be explained next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{L}=\mathbf{M}\hat{\omega}+\left(\hat{g}-\hat{x}\right)\times\hat{p}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term describes the rotational angular momentum, the angular momentum
 imparted by the spin of the body.
 The second term describes the translational angular momentum, which is
 used when it is part of a system of bodies.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary constant value with respect to the entire system (i.e.
 for evaluating the total angular momentum for a system of multiple bodies).
 For the purposes of a single-body system, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 can be set to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

, which completely eliminates the translational component.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
subsection{Second Moment Of Inertia Tensor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Second Moment Of Inertia Tensor
\series default
 is a diagonalizable matrix which defines the relation between angular momentum
 and angular velocity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 be this matrix, and it will be hereafter referred to as the 
\series bold
inertia tensor
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{L}=\mathbf{M}\hat{\omega}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To develop an intuition for the inertia tensor, it is useful to explore
 some of its properties.
 As mentioned above, the matrix is diagonalizable.
 This means there exists an invertible matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{T}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}=\mathbf{T}^{-1}\mathbf{M}\mathbf{T}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

similar
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrices and thus share eigenvalues.
 The eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{T}\hat{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{v}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Finding the eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix is trivial, as they are plainly
 sitting on the diagonal.
 The eigenvalues for an inertia tensor are referred to as the 
\series bold
principle moments of inertia
\series default
.
 The corresponding eigenvectors are called the 
\series bold
principle axes
\series default
.
 It should be noted that the inertia tensor is stationary relative to the
 orientation of its body -- if the body rotates, the inertia tensor must
 rotate identically in order to preserve relative orientation.
\end_layout

