\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Linear Kinetic Energy
\series default
 is a (strictly non-negative) scalar value which specifies the amount of
 energy a body has due to its linear motion.
 The equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{t}=\frac{1}{2}m\hat{v}\cdot\hat{v}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is obtained by the integral of the body's velocity with respect to its momentum:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{t}=\int\hat{v}\cdot\mathbf{d\hat{p}}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Rotational Kinetic Energy
\series default
 is a (strictly non-negative(?)) scalar value which specifies the amount
 of energy a body has due to its rotational motion.
 It is obtained in a similar way to its linear counterpart.
 The equation is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
E_{r}=\frac{1}{2}\hat{\omega}\cdot\left(\mathbf{M}\hat{\omega}\right)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Definition: Total Kinetic Energy
\series default
 is the scalar sum of linear and rotational kinetic energies.
 It specifies the total amount of energy possessed by a body due to motion.
\end_layout

