\begin_layout Standard
In dealing rotating bodies, certain situations require knowledge of the
 linear velocity of a point in a body which is rotating.
 Since rotation imparts a curved path to any point outside the axis of rotation,
 it is only valid to talk about the instantaneous linear velocity for a
 point in a rotating velocity (the derivative).
 Fortunately, calculus is not required to solve for this value, if we know
 all the properties of the body at the time we wish to calculate the aforementio
ned value.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 be the linear velocity of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 in a rotating body with center of gravity 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}$
\end_inset

, linear velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{v}$
\end_inset

, and angular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\hat{s}=\hat{v}+\hat{\omega}\times\left(\hat{R}-\hat{g}\right)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

