\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Omega_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Omega_{2}}$
\end_inset

 for the post-collision angular velocity vectors).
 From here on after, when a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 subscript is used, it will indicate that it can be replaced with the index
 of any of the bodies, indicating that the symbol applies to that body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplify things a bit, express 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V_{2}}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the difference from their pre-collision counterparts, all in
 terms of momentum.
 An unknown scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

 for each body is introduced to give the magnitude of the change in linear
 momentum.
 Also listed are permutations of the equation which will be useful later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{k}\hat{N}=m_{k}\hat{V_{k}}-m_{k}\hat{v_{k}}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
m_{k}\hat{V_{k}}=m_{k}\hat{v_{k}}+c_{k}\hat{N}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{V_{k}}=\hat{v_{k}}+\frac{c_{k}}{m_{k}}\hat{N}\label{eq:Vk}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is valid, because the change in linear momentum is along the normal
 vector.
 
