\begin_layout Standard
Inelastic collisions are ones that result in a loss of kinetic energy (kinetic
 energy is not conserved).
 Perfectly inelastic collisions satisfy the minimum requirements for non-interpe
netration of the involved bodies.
 For example, two lumps of clay hitting each other is an inelastic collision.
 This example isn't exactly analogous, since the clay lumps aren't rigid
 bodies, so some of the kinetic energy of the clay goes into body deformation,
 sound, heat, etc.
 Inelastic, rigid body collisions are pathological in that sense, because
 the loss of kinetic energy implies the body is deformable.
 But for the sake of computer simulation (and mathematical interest), it
 is worthwhile to explore.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section is a continuation of the work in the previous section.
 It is branched here into inelastic and elastic cases, because the entire
 previous section is common to both collision types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we jump into the condition for rotating, perfectly inelastic collisions,
 we will first develop an intuition of what the condition is for non-rotating,
 perfectly inelastic collisions.
 If a perfectly inelastic body (a lump of clay is near enough to perfectly
 inelastic for this example) is dropped to the ground, it will not bounce
 back whatsoever.
 From this we can deduce that the velocity between the two bodies (relative
 velocity) must be zero after the collision.
 This one-dimensional example is not sufficient however.
 Suppose the ground is covered with something that makes it completely frictionl
ess.
 We throw the lump of clay horizontally such that it hits the ground at
 an angle.
 Because the surface is frictionless, there will be no lateral force imparted
 to the lump of clay.
 The only force imparted is to keep it from penetrating the ground.
 The force is in the collision's normal direction.
 Therefore we can deduce that the normal component of velocity must be zero
 after the collision.
\end_layout

