section{Conservation Of Angular Momentum Of A Single Body}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tensor matrix which describes the second moment of inertia transforms
 the angular velocity vector of a body into the corresponding angular momentum
 vector.
 The resulting angular momentum vector may not necessarily be colinear with
 the angular velocity vector.
 However, angular momentum must always be conserved, even when the system
 involves only one body.
 The angular velocity vector of the body must change in such a way so that
 the angular momentum vector remains constant.
 This indicates that the angular velocity vector is a function of time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\mathbf{d}}{\mathbf{dt}}\hat{L}=\frac{\mathbf{d}}{\mathbf{dt}}\mathbf{M}\hat{\omega}=0\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inertia tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 remains fixed relative to the rotating body, so any rotation applied to
 the body must be applied to the inertia tensor as well.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 is a function of time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y\\
z\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 be the rotation matrix which rotates 3-space around the axis 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}$
\end_inset

 through the angle given by the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

